<hr>

<h3><b>Journal or publisher requirements for research data</b></h3>

<p>When you publish a research article in a journal, you may be asked to deposit and share the supporting data in a data repository.</p>

<p>You may be asked to do certain actions with your research data. Journals or publishers may ask for:</p>

<ul>
    <li>Data to be deposited in a data repository</li>
    <li>Data to be deposited into a specific repository</li>
    <li>A persistent identifier (e.g. DOI) for datasets</li>
    <li>A data availability statement to be included in the publication</li>
    <li>Data to be shared or made available to others</li>
    <li>Data access as part of the peer review process</li>
</ul>

<p>Check in the <b>Instructions for Authors</b> section of a journal's website to determine if there are requirements or recommendations related to research data for a particular title. We encourage you to review publisher requirements early in your research process.</p>

<p>The most common action required by publishers is data sharing, usually done by depositing data in a repository. Learn more <a href="https://guides.library.utoronto.ca/rdm/deposit-share">about depositing and sharing data.</a></p>

<script>
// JavaScript for accordion functionality
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
    const accordionHeaders = document.querySelectorAll('.accordion-header');
    
    accordionHeaders.forEach(header => {
        header.addEventListener('click', function() {
            const accordion = this.closest('.accordion');
            const isCurrentlyOpen = accordion.classList.contains('open');
            
            // Toggle the current accordion
            if (isCurrentlyOpen) {
                accordion.classList.remove('open');
                this.setAttribute('aria-expanded', 'false');
            } else {
                accordion.classList.add('open');
                this.setAttribute('aria-expanded', 'true');
            }
        });
    });
});
</script>

